            <div class="col-md-12 text-center">
                <h1 id="DescriptionText" style="margin-bottom: 5rem;">Description</h1>
                <p>
                    <i>Verticillium dahliae</i> has a wide range of hosts, among which herbaceous plants and perennial
                    wood are
                    included, affecting more than 300 species, including cotton, strawberries, raspberries, blueberries,
                    potatoes, lettuce, among others; even more importantly, its effects are worldwide.<sup><a
                            href="#absRef8">2</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    China is the world’s second biggest cotton producer and Verticillium wilt’s rates have been
                    increasing
                    in the past decade. <i>V. dahliae</i>, as well as another wilt disease, have had a great impact in
                    the
                    country’s cotton production, losing more than 150,00 tons per year.<sup><a
                            href="#absRef9">3</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Meanwhile, in the US, cotton wilt causes annual losses around 0.5% and 3.5% of the crops at a
                    national
                    level. In certain states, such as New Mexico, these rates have reached 5% and in Alabama, cropping
                    fields have decreased 1.5% of its extension; these losses translate into roughly 3 million
                    dollars.<sup><a href="#absRef10">4</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Speaking of Mexico, cotton production is highly important seeing that the amount produced accounts
                    for
                    80.67& of total national demand; in 2018, cotton production represented a profit over
                    $10,343,005,600
                    for the country.<sup><a href="#absRef11">5</a></sup> Chihuahua is the biggest cotton producer of
                    Mexico with its yield being 70.2% of all
                    national production.<sup><a href="#absRef7">1</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Currently, there is not any <i>Verticillium</i> specialized and aimed product, cotton producers turn
                    to the
                    conventional approach. They add agrochemicals to their crops, without any proper instructions and in
                    unawareness of the potential consequences. This elicits unwanted effects, such as elimination
                    non-target
                    organisms, and affectation of the food chain, high risks to the environment and human health. Even,
                    people are being affected too, over 3 million agricultors suffer from serious poisoning, while 25
                    million suffer from mild poisoning.<sup><a href="#absRef12">6</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Also, trophic chains have been affected by this. A given example is the bee population reducing
                    29%-36%
                    due to excessive use of triazoles.<sup><a href="#absRef13">7</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Another method employed to reduce <i>Verticillium</i> caused infections is crop rotation which
                    consists of
                    alternating plants with different nutritional needs in one place during different cycles, however it
                    can
                    result in disease propagation. Also, a frequent used technique is solarization, it refers to soil
                    disinfestation through the heat generated from the solar energy captured; nevertheless, despite its
                    positive outcomes, demands a great amount of time.<sup><a href="#absRef14">8</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row text-center">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <h2>What about this fungus?</h2>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <p>
                    <i>Verticillium dahliae</i> is stimulated by humid soils and temperatures between 21°C and 27°C
                    (70°F-80°C). This makes tropical and subtropical regions a suitable environment for its growth. The
                    fungus can overwinter as mycelium in perennial hosts, plant debris, and vegetative propagative
                    parts.<sup><a href="#absRef15">9</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row text-center">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <h3>Life cycle and action mechanism</h3>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <p>
                    It can be divided into three phases:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Latent phase:</strong> as a microsclerotia, made from melanin, Verticillium can survive in
                    the soil from a
                    single year to over two decades. Once roots exudates are found in the surrounding, the
                    microsclerotia starts to germinate and spreads inside the plant through its mycelial form or as
                    spores called microconidia. Once this happens, it travels into the plant’s vascular system,
                    worsening the infection.<sup><a href="#absRef16">10</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Parasitic phase:</strong> onizes the plant’s structure, especially its roots and stems,
                    producing in turn more microsclerotia. Infected plant tissue turns necrotic since the vascular
                    system is obstructed with mycelia, conidias, and fungal metabolism byproducts. The pathogen itself
                    produces a glue-like substance that also obstructs the plant’s vessels, provoking water blockage and
                    tissue wilting.<sup><a href="#absRef17">11</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Saprophytic phase:</strong> the plant dies, therefore the microsclerotia gets into the soil
                    and starts with
                    the cycle all over again.<sup><a href="#absRef18">12</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Usually, Verticillium wilt symptoms vary among hosts, but certain common symptoms can be pinpointed:
                    premature leaf chlorosis, necrosis and vascular discoloration in stems and roots.<sup><a
                            href="#absRef19">13</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Looking forward to helping our environment and cotton industry, a systemic, preventive and treating
                    biofungicide using recombinant antifungal peptides as active ingredients is sought. So, in order to
                    fulfil our objective, the following methodology was designed with the purpose of turning our project
                    from an idea to reality.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <p>
                    <strong>BioBrick<sup>TM</sup> Design:</strong> a total of five DNA sequences were designed to
                    express
                    recombinantly the peptides
                    in <i>E. coli</i>. The constructs count with the essential parts needed for their correct
                    translation into
                    proteins, purification, and proper folding. Recombinant production of disulfide bonded peptides,
                    like PsDEF1 and WAMP1b, can be complicated in prokaryotic systems, thus we have as well created DNA
                    sequences for the co-expression of these peptides with Erv1p, a disulfide bond forming
                    protein.<sup><a href="#absRef20">14</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <strong><i>E. coli</i> Cells Transformation:</strong> chemically competent <i>E. coli</i> cells are
                    prepared and transformed with
                    our vectors. <i>E. coli</i> BL21 (DE3) was chosen as a chassis for the expression of AtPFN1 for
                    being ideal
                    for protein expression. In the case of PsDef1 and WAMP1b, <i>E. coli</i> SHuffle T7 Express, a
                    specially
                    designed strain to aid in the proper formation disulfide bonds, was chosen as an expression vector.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <strong>IPTG induced protein expression:</strong> after the cells are correctly transformed,
                    expression of the
                    peptides can be induced and controlled by Isopropyl β-D-1-thiogalactopyranoside (IPTG); BL21 (DE3)
                    and SHuffle are T7 expression strains. Once IPTG is added to these strains, T7 RNA polymerase is
                    produced and capable of transcribing downstream of promoters like those found in the DNA
                    constructs.<sup><a href="#absRef21">15</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <strong>Soluble Protein Extraction:</strong> after induction and a period of incubation, cells are
                    lysed through a
                    series of freeze/thaw cycles with the help of a lysis solution and sonication. The lysate is then
                    centrifuged to obtain the cells soluble proteins in the supernatant.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <strong>Protein Purification:</strong> our peptides are designed to be expressed as fusion proteins
                    with a 6x
                    His-Tag. This allows the peptides to be purified through immobilized metal affinity chromatography,
                    a purification procedure based on the interaction of metal ions with polyhistidine sequences in
                    tagged proteins.<sup><a href="#absRef22">16</a></sup>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <strong>Antifungal Assay:</strong> next, the antifungal activity of the peptides is tested against
                    <i>V. dahliae.</i> A
                    spore suspension is treated with the purified peptides individually as well as a mixture of all
                    three of them to prove their collaborative effect against the fungus.
                </p>

                <!-- LINK TO PROJECT DESIGN PAGE -->

                <p>
                    <strong>Delivery:</strong> nanoencapsulation has been shown to be a promising alternative to deliver
                    active
                    ingredients more efficiently and accurately. This is the reason or purpose is to get nanoencapsulate
                    our recombinant peptides by creating a chitosan-poly(lactice) copolymer nanocapsule. <sup><a
                            href="#absRef23">17</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row text-center">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <h2>
                    What are our peptides?
                </h2>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <h3>
                    <strong>WAMP1b</strong>
                </h3>
                <br>
                <p>
                    WAMP1b is part of the WAMPs antimicrobial peptides, a type of chitinase-like peptides from <i>
                        Triticum
                        kiharae.
                    </i> These antimicrobial peptides are also called hevein-like proteins due to their similarity
                    to hevein and to having a chitin binding site similar to chitinases.<sup><a
                            href="#absRef24">18</a></sup> The peptide’s action mechanism consists in the inhibition of
                    fungalysins, fungal defense metalloproteases. Fungalysins cleave chitinases, plant proteins that
                    degrade chitin found in the fungal cell wall.<sup><a href="#absRef25">19</a></sup> Since <i>V.
                        dahliae</i>
                    produces fungalysin<sup><a href="#absRef26">20</a></sup>, WAMP1b can be used to inhibit the
                    fungus’ defense system, thus suppressing its pathogenicity.
                </p>

                <h3>
                    <strong>AtPFN1</strong>
                </h3>
                <br>
                <p>
                    AtPFN1 is a profilin protein from <i>Arabidopsis thaliana</i>. These protein bind to chitin, an
                    important
                    mechanism for their antifungal action. It degrades spore and hyphal cell wall, then accumulating in
                    the cytoplasm where it generates reactive oxygen species and induces apoptosis. AtPFN1 has been
                    shown to break down fungal cell walls, even when it is in its dormant, spore phase, ideally
                    preventing the spread of <i>V. dahliae</i> and other fungi.<sup><a href="#absRef27">21</a></sup>
                </p>

                <h3>
                    <strong>PsDef1</strong>
                </h3>
                <br>
                <p>
                    PsDef1 stands for <i>Pinus sylvestris</i> Defensin 1, a plant defensin that has been shown to
                    produce
                    morphological changes to fungi mycelium. It presents significant similarities to RsAFP2 (<i>
                        Raphanus
                        sativus
                    </i> antifungal peptide). RsAFP2, upon binding to GlcCer, produces reactive oxygen species inside
                    the fungal cell, effectively killing it from the inside.<sup><a href="#absRef28">22</a></sup>
                    Additionally, PsDef1 contains 4 disulfide bonds which grant it resilience against environmental
                    changes.<sup><a href="#absRef29">23</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <p>
                    In such a way that, the peptides’ nature and the delivery properties of the nanocapsule wilt allow
                    the biofungicide to act both as preventive and treating product during planting season.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Once the nanoencapsulation is achieved, the product could be lyophilized and turned into wettable
                    powder (WP). In this presentation it can be applied to the crops through the watering system. After
                    a field research, we realized people involved with the crops knew about new agricultural products
                    through their technical assessor, who learned about them through distributors. Considering this
                    informational chain, our aim is that the final product reaches agrochemical products development
                    company.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Finally, bibliographic and field research were carried out, seeking for the final product to assure
                    the greatest benefit for all parties involved (textile industry or cotton consumers, marketers,
                    cotton crops producers, environment, etc…). Through interviews the producer’s wishes were validated
                    and through detailed consultation of NOMs like NOM-232-SSA1-2009 and NOM-045-SSA1-1993, the proposal
                    of a law-abiding project was sought. Likewise, a through risk analysis was developed, considering
                    any unfavorable situation our project might pose.
                </p>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

